Then I will talk about some of the work that's being done at my center on

12
00:00:42.320 --> 00:00:43.160
social capital.

13
00:00:44.070 --> 00:00:47.690
And then Melissa Bondy from Stanford University is going to talk about

14
00:00:47.720 --> 00:00:49.220
targeting very upstream

15
00:00:51.760 --> 00:00:53.490
factors in relationship to

16
00:00:54.740 --> 00:00:57.780
poverty and its relationship with cancer mortality.

17
00:00:58.089 --> 00:01:01.560
And then we'll have time for a panel discussion at the end.

18
00:01:03.180 --> 00:01:06.500
So just to make sure that we're all talking about the same thing, I just wanted to

19
00:01:06.520 --> 00:01:10.350
share what the definition that we are using with respect to persistent poverty.

20
00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:14.900
So the US Department of Agriculture defines persistent poverty

21
00:01:14.980 --> 00:01:18.810
as census tracts where more than 20% of the population is

22
00:01:18.840 --> 00:01:22.780
underneath the federal poverty line and has been in that condition

23
00:01:22.820 --> 00:01:26.440
for 30 plus years. And so throughout these

24
00:01:26.460 --> 00:01:30.360
presentations, when we talk about persistent poverty areas, that's what

25
00:01:30.440 --> 00:01:31.480
we are talking about.

26
00:01:33.040 --> 00:01:37.020
And there are many characteristics that we see in persistent poverty areas

27
00:01:37.400 --> 00:01:40.340
that are associated with cancer and cancer mortality.

28
00:01:40.400 --> 00:01:44.020
So many of these areas may have structural factors, different

29
00:01:44.060 --> 00:01:47.840
demographic factors or environmental factors, and you'll hear about some of those

30
00:01:47.940 --> 00:01:48.420
today.

31
00:01:49.590 --> 00:01:52.680
They also tend to have limited access to healthcare,

32
00:01:53.640 --> 00:01:57.340
prevalence differences with respect to risk factors for cancer that can

33
00:01:57.420 --> 00:01:59.720
also contribute to poor mortality,

34
00:02:00.760 --> 00:02:04.670
and we have evidence of higher cancer incidence rates as well as higher

35
00:02:04.760 --> 00:02:08.741
mortality rates from cancer in these areas that are characterized as

36
00:02:08.759 --> 00:02:10.140
persistent poverty areas.

37
00:02:11.570 --> 00:02:15.350
Some of the initial work that really stimulated additional research in

38
00:02:15.400 --> 00:02:19.020
this area was published by colleagues at the National Cancer

39
00:02:19.100 --> 00:02:22.720
Institute, including Shoba Srinivasan and Bob

40
00:02:22.820 --> 00:02:26.800
Croyle, that really showed that there are a number of cancer sites when you look

41
00:02:26.900 --> 00:02:30.300
at people living in persistent poverty areas versus

42
00:02:30.360 --> 00:02:34.049
non-persistent poverty areas, that there are higher

43
00:02:34.140 --> 00:02:37.820
levels of cancer mortality. And so you can see those different cancer

44
00:02:37.860 --> 00:02:39.480
sites for which this is true.

45
00:02:41.800 --> 00:02:45.420
So we know that persistent poverty is a significant determinant of

46
00:02:45.460 --> 00:02:49.260
cancer outcomes. We also know that the majority of cancer

47
00:02:49.420 --> 00:02:53.100
prevention opportunities are really focused more at the individual

48
00:02:53.200 --> 00:02:56.700
level. And this initiative that came from the National Cancer

49
00:02:56.760 --> 00:03:00.420
Institute really put out a charge to shift

50
00:03:00.480 --> 00:03:04.280
towards thinking about the causes of the causes and really charged

51
00:03:04.340 --> 00:03:07.960
people with thinking about how to intervene upstream, really on more

52
00:03:07.980 --> 00:03:11.540
social, economic drivers that may influence

53
00:03:12.420 --> 00:03:14.960
cancer outcomes. And so as part of that,

54
00:03:15.820 --> 00:03:19.600
a number of centers put in applications to really try and study

55
00:03:19.620 --> 00:03:23.560
these interventions that would target structural and institutional factors.

56
00:03:25.020 --> 00:03:25.540
There were five

57
00:03:26.820 --> 00:03:30.780
NCI-funded centers across the United States. You can see them here.

58
00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:34.700
These are the names of those five centers.

59
00:03:34.730 --> 00:03:38.580
So the three of us on this panel represent the top three

60
00:03:39.360 --> 00:03:42.880
centers. There are two others that are not represented here today.

61
00:03:42.980 --> 00:03:45.940
I just wanted to make sure that they are represented.

62
00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:49.850
So those are the Be Well Acres Homes from MD Anderson and the

63
00:03:49.900 --> 00:03:53.280
CARE Center at the University of Alabama in Birmingham.

64
00:03:55.700 --> 00:03:58.980
I think many people here are probably familiar with the Warnecke Model.

65
00:03:59.140 --> 00:04:02.820
Our PPI, this Persistent Poverty Initiative network, came

66
00:04:02.920 --> 00:04:06.760
together to really try and put together a framework to describe how persistent

67
00:04:06.770 --> 00:04:09.500
poverty can impact cancer burden.

68
00:04:10.160 --> 00:04:13.480
And this is really built on top of the Warnecke Model

69
00:04:14.160 --> 00:04:17.870
and really highlights some of the many different levels that can

70
00:04:17.880 --> 00:04:21.171
contribute to cancer disparities.

71
00:04:22.320 --> 00:04:25.860
Our PPI initiative is laid on here so you can

72
00:04:25.900 --> 00:04:29.520
see what some of the targeted interventions are from

73
00:04:29.580 --> 00:04:29.960
this,

74
00:04:30.880 --> 00:04:34.180
focusing on different factors in terms of education,

75
00:04:34.800 --> 00:04:38.469
built environment, income supplementation, and you're going to hear about some of

76
00:04:38.520 --> 00:04:39.320
these today.

77
00:04:40.560 --> 00:04:43.740
And really, you can see at the bottom of this is community-engaged

78
00:04:43.780 --> 00:04:47.460
participation. And so as part of our panel today,

79
00:04:47.840 --> 00:04:51.540
David Wetter is really going to talk about community engagement to kick us off.

80
00:04:51.880 --> 00:04:54.980
I'm going to talk about the work at our center, which is focused more on the

81
00:04:55.020 --> 00:04:57.200
institutional context in this box.

82
00:04:57.600 --> 00:05:01.380
And then Melissa Bondy is going to talk about even further upstream, some of the

83
00:05:01.460 --> 00:05:04.880
social policies that can influence cancer

84
00:05:04.960 --> 00:05:05.520
outcomes.

85
00:05:06.980 --> 00:05:08.960
And so with that, I will turn it over to David Wetter.

86
00:05:15.700 --> 00:05:16.340
Good morning.

87
00:05:17.420 --> 00:05:21.360
I'm going to talk a little bit about how do you

88
00:05:21.460 --> 00:05:25.320
reach out to and work with both populations living in

89
00:05:25.420 --> 00:05:29.240
poverty and geographic areas that are characterized by persistent

90
00:05:29.340 --> 00:05:33.220
poverty. And there's lots of new engagement models that are

91
00:05:33.280 --> 00:05:37.220
coming out, and I'm going to be a little bit blasphemous

92
00:05:37.280 --> 00:05:40.180
because I actually think it's pretty simple to do this.

93
00:05:40.940 --> 00:05:43.020
And I'm going to tell you how we do it, and it's

94
00:05:43.960 --> 00:05:45.540
something that's worked very well.

95
00:05:45.880 --> 00:05:48.660
It's a very simple, very common sense framework.

96
00:05:49.900 --> 00:05:50.100
So,

97
00:05:51.020 --> 00:05:54.840
the Center for HOPE, which is where our center is located,

98
00:05:55.460 --> 00:05:58.160
both there and at Montana

99
00:05:59.440 --> 00:06:03.400
State University, is we bring communities and researchers together to create

100
00:06:03.480 --> 00:06:05.980
long-term solutions to improve the health of the broader

101
00:06:06.060 --> 00:06:08.174
population.And

102
00:06:08.984 --> 00:06:12.724
as you can see from that picture on the right, there's lots of places

103
00:06:12.784 --> 00:06:16.724
where that can go wrong. One of the places is with the

104
00:06:16.744 --> 00:06:18.124
community engagement piece.

105
00:06:19.704 --> 00:06:23.384
So first of all is identifying

106
00:06:23.544 --> 00:06:24.064
where

107
00:06:25.124 --> 00:06:28.904
populations living in persistent poverty and geographic areas

108
00:06:29.024 --> 00:06:32.804
characterized by persistent poverty are located and who serves

109
00:06:32.904 --> 00:06:36.704
them. So federally qualified health centers, many of you

110
00:06:36.764 --> 00:06:40.323
probably have heard of them. We call them community health centers in Utah because

111
00:06:40.384 --> 00:06:44.264
that's what they prefer. There are 14 systems in

112
00:06:44.384 --> 00:06:47.484
Utah shown all around that

113
00:06:48.324 --> 00:06:52.104
diagram. And then they're served by the Association for

114
00:06:52.184 --> 00:06:54.424
Utah Community Health or AUCH.

115
00:06:56.184 --> 00:06:59.404
Come on, there we go. Usually that gets a smile. Come on.

116
00:06:59.464 --> 00:07:00.644
That's a pretty cool name.

117
00:07:02.104 --> 00:07:05.524
They are the federally designated primary care association,

118
00:07:05.824 --> 00:07:09.684
and they provide technical assistance and training, et cetera, to all the

119
00:07:09.704 --> 00:07:11.384
community health centers around the state.

120
00:07:12.004 --> 00:07:15.954
So FQHCs, or I'm going to keep using the term CHCs,

121
00:07:16.664 --> 00:07:20.384
are phenomenal places to reach these kind of folks because

122
00:07:20.544 --> 00:07:24.264
they provide care regardless of their ability to pay.

123
00:07:25.684 --> 00:07:29.144
In Utah, there's 14 systems, over 60 primary care clinics.

124
00:07:29.484 --> 00:07:32.824
They care for about 140,000 patients, which is down about

125
00:07:33.044 --> 00:07:35.344
25,000 patients, which

126
00:07:36.404 --> 00:07:40.364
you might be able to guess some of the reasons for that. It's very unfortunate.

127
00:07:40.924 --> 00:07:44.844
But the demographics are also very different than what

128
00:07:44.924 --> 00:07:47.724
I know you all are thinking about when you think of Utah.

129
00:07:48.664 --> 00:07:52.324
Because we've got 52% of their patients live below the federal

130
00:07:52.444 --> 00:07:55.044
poverty line, over half are Latino,

131
00:07:56.104 --> 00:07:59.284
almost half are best served in a language other than English,

132
00:07:59.844 --> 00:08:03.564
and 45% are uninsured. And I want to highlight that

133
00:08:03.744 --> 00:08:07.224
45% uninsured because nationally, the rate of

134
00:08:07.264 --> 00:08:10.984
uninsurance at FQHCs is 19%. In

135
00:08:11.044 --> 00:08:14.194
Utah, it's 45. What that means is our

136
00:08:14.264 --> 00:08:17.934
CHCs have to do a heck of a lot with

137
00:08:18.043 --> 00:08:20.944
very, very few financial resources.

138
00:08:21.004 --> 00:08:24.824
So they're actually mind-bogglingly impressive when

139
00:08:24.864 --> 00:08:28.524
you get the chance to work with them on how they're doing amazing

140
00:08:28.624 --> 00:08:32.584
work, unbelievably dedicated, passionate people with not very

141
00:08:32.624 --> 00:08:33.204
much money.

142
00:08:35.544 --> 00:08:38.684
So that's who we partner with. And here's our model.

143
00:08:39.204 --> 00:08:42.684
Again, very, very simple. And all I want to do is

144
00:08:42.744 --> 00:08:46.524
highlight a few of the key partnership characteristics, a few of the key

145
00:08:46.564 --> 00:08:50.444
engagement activities, and some of the things we've learned in working

146
00:08:50.504 --> 00:08:50.964
with them

147
00:08:51.844 --> 00:08:53.644
over about the last nine and a half years.

148
00:08:53.704 --> 00:08:57.324
I came to Utah and Huntsman Cancer

149
00:08:57.384 --> 00:08:58.904
Institute nine and a half years ago.

150
00:09:00.864 --> 00:09:02.024
So first of all,

151
00:09:03.084 --> 00:09:06.844
this is actually the key thing. It's actually the very

152
00:09:06.884 --> 00:09:07.504
simple thing.

153
00:09:08.884 --> 00:09:11.714
Folks will partner with you if you address their

154
00:09:11.764 --> 00:09:15.344
priorities. Academics are not very good at that.

155
00:09:15.384 --> 00:09:18.804
We often want to push what we want to study onto the

156
00:09:18.844 --> 00:09:20.664
partners. And surprisingly,

157
00:09:21.764 --> 00:09:23.044
they don't want to partner with you.

158
00:09:23.584 --> 00:09:27.444
It's actually really, really easy if you

159
00:09:27.524 --> 00:09:30.364
address their priorities. And if you think about it,

160
00:09:31.284 --> 00:09:35.144
if all of you are writing a grant and you really need statistical support

161
00:09:35.644 --> 00:09:39.624
and you ask me for help, I'm a behavioral scientist, can't balance a

162
00:09:39.684 --> 00:09:43.344
checkbook. And I go, "Well, I can't provide statistical

163
00:09:43.424 --> 00:09:45.564
support, but I can teach you all about behavior change.

164
00:09:45.644 --> 00:09:49.104
Let's do behavior change." You're going to go, "No, I need statistical support."

165
00:09:49.724 --> 00:09:50.864
You ain't going to partner with me.

166
00:09:51.924 --> 00:09:54.684
So this is the number one key thing.

167
00:09:55.884 --> 00:09:57.804
And then the other thing is share.

168
00:09:58.724 --> 00:10:02.504
This is another thing that academics, in my experience, aren't always great

169
00:10:02.584 --> 00:10:05.264
at, sharing resources, data, et cetera.

170
00:10:05.294 --> 00:10:07.044
And I'll give you just a couple of examples.

171
00:10:07.524 --> 00:10:11.344
Our very first project was a large PCORI pragmatic trial.

172
00:10:12.624 --> 00:10:16.464
And in that, we brought in about $10 million to the state to help

173
00:10:16.524 --> 00:10:17.884
address tobacco control.

174
00:10:18.904 --> 00:10:22.804
So what the state did was actually take some of the resources

175
00:10:22.844 --> 00:10:26.424
that they were using for tobacco control that we could offset with the

176
00:10:26.484 --> 00:10:30.364
grant and move that money into providing cessation medications

177
00:10:30.384 --> 00:10:34.024
for folks who were uninsured. So it was a

178
00:10:34.064 --> 00:10:37.834
really beautiful synergistic sharing of data, resources.

179
00:10:38.533 --> 00:10:42.044
Similarly, during COVID, we had three RADx

180
00:10:42.344 --> 00:10:46.264
grants from NIH, which are addressing underserved populations.

181
00:10:47.024 --> 00:10:50.944
And we met with the state at least weekly and many times twice a

182
00:10:50.984 --> 00:10:52.964
week because if you'll remember during COVID,

183
00:10:53.944 --> 00:10:57.344
where you could test and who could test changed

184
00:10:57.484 --> 00:11:01.384
literally week by week by week. So we

185
00:11:01.424 --> 00:11:05.244
did whatever we needed to do to address what was going on there, and I'll

186
00:11:05.264 --> 00:11:07.204
actually come back to that a little bit later on.

187
00:11:08.554 --> 00:11:11.604
And then finally, we've provided millions and millions of dollars through our

188
00:11:11.644 --> 00:11:15.244
funding with AUCH and the CHCs to provide

189
00:11:15.284 --> 00:11:19.084
resources to buy a population health management

190
00:11:19.184 --> 00:11:22.914
system, which ties together all the data from all the CHCs

191
00:11:23.004 --> 00:11:26.814
across the state. So it really lets them start to do a

192
00:11:26.884 --> 00:11:29.264
lot more big data,

193
00:11:30.394 --> 00:11:33.964
targeted cohorts across the entire state, across these 14

194
00:11:34.004 --> 00:11:37.444
independent systems. And I should have mentioned that because what's unique

195
00:11:37.504 --> 00:11:39.014
about the CHCs,

196
00:11:39.924 --> 00:11:42.884
they're not a single system. They're not a Kaiser.

197
00:11:42.914 --> 00:11:46.884
They're not one giant large CHC. They can all choose to partner or

198
00:11:47.024 --> 00:11:49.784
not partner with you independently.

199
00:11:52.144 --> 00:11:53.944
So the other thing is

200
00:11:55.904 --> 00:11:59.700
respecting their expertise.These folks are

201
00:12:00.040 --> 00:12:02.320
very dedicated. They've been doing this a long time.

202
00:12:02.360 --> 00:12:05.160
They're getting their hands dirty every day.

203
00:12:05.740 --> 00:12:09.730
So we meet with the leadership at OUCH every few months to find out

204
00:12:09.740 --> 00:12:13.360
what their priorities are. And priorities at CHCs

205
00:12:13.440 --> 00:12:15.280
around the country are driven heavily

206
00:12:16.680 --> 00:12:20.460
by the funding that is available to them on whatever's happening

207
00:12:20.470 --> 00:12:24.080
that year. So you have to be on your toes, reaching out to them

208
00:12:24.180 --> 00:12:26.239
constantly, find out what they care about.

209
00:12:26.940 --> 00:12:30.860
Their priorities are also driven by what are called UDS measures,

210
00:12:30.940 --> 00:12:34.360
which are their national reporting on how well they're doing.

211
00:12:36.520 --> 00:12:40.340
Every quarter, we also meet with a patient advisory group and a studies

212
00:12:40.380 --> 00:12:44.220
advisory group, and the patient advisory group is nothing but

213
00:12:44.320 --> 00:12:48.270
patients. We get everybody else out of the room other than the scientists and

214
00:12:48.300 --> 00:12:51.959
the patients, and they will tell you what they think, and they will be

215
00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:53.140
exceedingly blunt.

216
00:12:54.100 --> 00:12:58.040
They will tell you that they feel judged by their providers if they talk about

217
00:12:58.900 --> 00:13:01.940
alcohol use or tobacco use, so they will just flat out lie.

218
00:13:02.900 --> 00:13:06.860
So it really helps us to get that feedback because we

219
00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:10.900
use that in our training for providers and clinic staff about how to be

220
00:13:10.960 --> 00:13:13.980
non-judgmental in working with these populations.

221
00:13:14.520 --> 00:13:18.340
We also have a studies advisory committee, which includes those patients, but

222
00:13:18.400 --> 00:13:21.300
also representatives from all the organizations we work with.

223
00:13:21.920 --> 00:13:25.720
And we vet lots and lots of stuff with them, and they,

224
00:13:25.940 --> 00:13:29.520
again, have no problem telling us when we're doing something stupid

225
00:13:30.020 --> 00:13:33.880
or have wording that we thought was really brilliant, and they will tell

226
00:13:33.940 --> 00:13:37.540
us that they hate it. So it's really good to have these kinds of

227
00:13:37.580 --> 00:13:41.380
feedback loops because they know their clinic staff and they know their

228
00:13:41.460 --> 00:13:41.980
patients.

229
00:13:42.880 --> 00:13:46.800
We have a weekly meeting that includes multiple projects, includes members of OUCH,

230
00:13:46.880 --> 00:13:50.180
CHCs, et cetera, and that's really getting into the

231
00:13:50.580 --> 00:13:52.560
nitty-gritty of implementing projects.

232
00:13:52.680 --> 00:13:53.480
And then finally,

233
00:13:54.820 --> 00:13:58.760
when we first got there, we did something really unique, and it has been

234
00:13:58.860 --> 00:14:00.000
a spectacular

235
00:14:00.860 --> 00:14:04.500
thing for us. This woman right there,

236
00:14:05.180 --> 00:14:07.919
Tracy Saperas, is an employee of OUCH.

237
00:14:08.460 --> 00:14:12.360
She spent about 10 years working on the front lines in the CHCs, and

238
00:14:12.400 --> 00:14:16.360
when we got our first big grant, we jointly funded her through the Center

239
00:14:16.420 --> 00:14:19.660
for HOPE, through OUCH, and through the State Department of Health and Human

240
00:14:19.740 --> 00:14:23.250
Services. And she provided the link between all of us,

241
00:14:23.620 --> 00:14:27.420
and she has just been instrumental in bringing CHCs on board

242
00:14:27.480 --> 00:14:31.420
because they trust her, and she has no problem telling us when we have crappy

243
00:14:31.540 --> 00:14:35.220
ideas. So we work with her to vet, get good

244
00:14:35.300 --> 00:14:39.180
ideas, and then we can take them to her to tell us

245
00:14:39.220 --> 00:14:42.920
how they're doing, and then to the CHCs, and they fly really well.

246
00:14:43.300 --> 00:14:47.190
And so before COVID, she spent four days a week in our office with us.

247
00:14:47.560 --> 00:14:50.120
